newsitem.title: USA: U.S. MUNICIPAL FOCUS - Prices end down 1/8 to 1/4.
newsitem.headline: U.S. MUNICIPAL FOCUS - Prices end down 1/8 to 1/4.

text.p: U.S. municipal bond prices ended 1/8 to 1/4 point lower but avoided U.S. Treasuries' deeper slide Tuesday, while new deals appeared to garner good demand.
"One of the Fed Governors, (Janet) Yellen, came out and talked about inflation in the air. Treasuries traded down, munis traded down," a trader said.
Though the trader judged muni cash down 1/4 point, bonds remain scarce, he said.
"I think it's really a supply trade right here. I just don't think there's a lot of munis to knock us down with, so whatever is around sort of gets taken up," the trader said.
A municipal analyst said high-grade issues exited the session slightly easier, while dollar bonds lost 1/4 point. Activity was moderate, he said.

In debt futures, the December municipal contract closed down 10/32 at 111-21/32. The December T-bond contract closed down 18/32 at 106-21/32. The MOB spread was 160 ticks. In the government market, the benchmark 30-year bond was down 15/32 at 95-17/32 to yield 7.11 percent.
New issue pricing was "firm" on both negotiated and competitive offerings, the analyst said. A trader said while "there is some calendar this week," deals appear to be going "reasonably well."

Tuesday's biggest new issue was a $389.3 million, Washington Public Power Supply System offering. Goldman Sachs & Co repriced the offering, lowering yields in several maturities and cutting the top yield in 2012 to 5.91 percent from 5.95 percent.
A trader said the offering appeared to go well.

"We had good orders for the deal, and they were able to reprice some (maturities)," he said. "It seems like all the other transactions are going well. I think there's still good demand for municipals, or so it seems."

Several competitive issues also priced Tuesday. Lehman Brothers won $100 million Mayfield, Ky., variable rate multi-city lease revenue refunding bonds. The offering, which was not formally reoffered to investors, consisted of a single 2026 maturity with a 3.5 percent coupon.

Lehman also won $97.9 million Clark County, Nev., general obligation bonds at a true interest cost of 5.832 percent. It also won an $83 million Pinellas County, Fla., offering at a true interest cost of 5.389 percent.

In the short-term market, Fleet Securities Inc won $85 million of Suffolk County, N.Y.'s $95 million of tax anticipation notes, according to market sources. Oppenheimer & Co won the remaining $10 million. Fleet's net interest cost was 3.9905 percent, while Oppenheimer's was a 3.9868 percent.
Turning to Wednesday, 14 negotiated sales totaling $513 million are scheduled. A $134 million Broward County, Fla., deal via PaineWebber Inc tops the list.
In competitive action, 15 deals are scheduled totaling $467 million. A $115 million Wisconsin offering leads Wednesday's list.
